J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; It occurs to me that to test the second behavior does not require mocking the classpath. We can have a degenerate event/listener design.
&gt; 
&gt; As the ClasspathWalker walks the classpath, it calls a method to signal that it found something on the classpath. (event source)
&gt; 
&gt; This signal handling method (event listener) then decides which kind of ClasspathEvent to create and send to the registered ClasspathEventListeners.
&gt; 
&gt; In this case, you can test the second behavior above without having to actually walk the classpath. Much nicer.
&gt; 
&gt; So the basic design is this:
&gt; 
&gt; ClasspathWalker
&gt;     walkClasspath(classpathRoot):
&gt;         // iterate over classpath items under the root
&gt;         // invoke foundSomething() with each thing you find
&gt; 
&gt;     ClasspathEvent makeClasspathEvent(foundThing):
&gt;         // decide which kind of ClasspathEvent to generate
&gt;   
&gt;     foundSomething(foundThing):
&gt;         classpathEvent = makeClasspathEvent(foundThing);
&gt;         notifyListeners(classpathEvent);
&gt; 
&gt; ClasspathWalkerListener
&gt;     onClasspathEvent(classpathEvent)
&gt; 
&gt; My tests would be like this.
&gt; 
&gt; * One TestCase class to verify ClasspathWalker.walkClasspath that tries various cases of classpath data; probably a parameterized test case -- however many special cases there are
&gt; 
&gt; * One TestCase class to verify ClasspathWalker.makeClasspathEvent for each different kind of thing I&#39;d find on the classpath
&gt; 
&gt; * foundSomething is too simple to break
&gt; 
&gt; * Tests for my implementation of ClasspathWalkerListener: each test simply sends a ClasspathEvent and verifies the behavior of the listener
&gt; 

I&#39;d probably create a MockClasspathWalkerListener, then write a test 
case that installs it into the ClassPathWalker, and verifies various 
cases of classpath data.  For each variation, the test would ask the 
MockClasspathWalkerListener if it really received the events I was 
expecting for the variation, as in:

public void testSomeClasspathVariation() {

   ClasspathWalker walker = new ClasspathWalker();
   MockClasspathWalkerListener listener =
       new MockClasspathWalkerListener();
   walker.addListener(listener);

   walker.walkClasspath(someClasspathVariation)

   assertTrue(listener.heard(someExpectedEvent));
}

Same intent, just a slightly more granular test.  And if I saw red for 
more than a couple minutes, I&#39;d start taking smaller steps by writing 
fine-grained tests such as those you mentioned.

Or maybe somebody already said this while I was heads-down coding...

